snippet.textDisplay: Nice, although I find the rendition by Musarrat Nazir (look it up on YouTube) much more compelling. The instrumentation there is much more raw and expressive, especially when it comes to the percussion and complexities of the rhythm/melody/singing, and retains the charm and intimacy of a dholki. I think using Western instrumentation/harmony for the sake of it can sometimes make it sound almost overproduced but less complex/emotive. Instead of the percussion/melody interrogating each other, the backing music using western harmony and rhythm requires it to become almost too sweet.
